<br>
You can paint it with a blue sky, yellow sun, and green trees on green hills.  It is sufficient yes, and you do get a feeling of satisfaction.  But, Imagine if you were to paint storm clouds, with lightning strikes.  Rain puddles, and maybe a cow on the hill stuck in a sinking pit of mud, desperately screaming as he stretches to the tree.  Now at first, the painting is unpleasant..but after time, you begin to understand the emotion inside.<br>
<br>
Coffee is definately acquired tastes, that can only be developed through experimenting with your pallete.  Those that drink Foldier's or Maxwell House 24/7 will never experience the definate flavor differences and what a good cup of coffee is.  Most of the coffees out there today in your grocery store are Arabica coffees with different flavorings.  If you feel that this coffee is too bitter, then it is best you try something more light, as Arabica is medium bodied.  Usually the contents will explain what type of coffee it is.   Lighter coffees are typically sweeter and less bitter.   I prefer a Yemen Mocha Latte with a little Bailey's to neutralize some of the bitterness(Not to be confused with Mocha which has chocolate in it, Yemen Mocha does not) which is a very aromatic, dark bodied, with a rich hearty flavor.     <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ottoemhatick>Ottoe Mhatick</A> at: 10/23/03 8:41 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=lorderfv>LorderFV</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/23/03 8:40 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2037.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Coffee</span><hr size=1> Ahh, it is the necture of the Gods... I don't mean the weak stuff you get at 7-11, but the home brews. It definitely is an acquired taste, but I like to brew up a mix of Dark French Roast and Hazelnut, at about one and a half times the amount specified. That is in the morning, one cup while I am getting ready for work, another on the commute. But that is about it for the day for caffeine, I may have a coke with lunch but the rest of the day is all water. <br>
