<br>
Then I thought: &quot;I haven't had my coffee yet.&quot; <br>
<br>
One Great One (24 ounces of crappy crappy but oh so lovely coffee from Dunkin Donuts) later and I'm Completely Fine. My mood is better, my little aches and pains are gone, hell, I'd say I might have even been a bit euphoric. <br>
<br>
(Friend of mine once painted the visual picture that caffeine *expanded* your veins, so when you quit coffee all the veins shrunk back to normal size and it felt like you were drowning in your own body.)<br>
<br>
I agree coffee is an acquired taste. I choked it down in high school. Somewhere along the line some kind of switch went off, though, and I really started to LIKE it. Now I love the smell, I love the taste. <br>
<br>
(Could just be the endless deterioration of my taste buds, though. My drink of choice is whiskey straight up. If I drink beer it's a stout. I only drink red wine voluntarily. I think I've done so much damage to myself I only really crave heavy, harsh tastes.) <br>
<br>
PoLest<br>
hardcore caffeine addict since 1995<br>
hasn't slept more than five hours since 1996 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=statholturris>Stathol Turris</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/23/03 11:29 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2037.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Ah, coffee. </span><hr size=1> Caffeine is my shepherd; I shall not doze. It maketh me to wake in green pastures: It leadeth me beyond the sleeping masses.<br>
<br>
It restoreth my buzz: It leadeth me in the paths of consciousness for its name's sake.<br>
<br>
Yea, though I walk through the valley of the shadow of addiction, I will fear no Equal (tm): For thou art with me; thy cream and thy sugar they comfort me.<br>
<br>
Thou preparest a carafe before me in the presence of Juan Valdez: Thou anointest my day with pep; my mug runneth over.<br>
<br>
Surely richness and taste shall follow me all the days of my life: and I will dwell in the House of Folger's forever. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=xethux>Xethux</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Tyrannical ruler of the Galaxy</span><br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/23/03 4:18 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2037.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Ah, coffee. </span><hr size=1> Coffee has always been a part of my life. As young as I can remember, I was given coffeemilk. (a mixture of mostly milk, with a little bit of coffee and sugar tossed in for flavor) I have no daily ritual about it, I am able to function without it, often will have tea rather than coffee (more and more so as the &quot;Seattle&quot; style flavor of burnt coffee becomes ever more widespread. Starbucks is some of the worst coffee in the world.), but I love a good cup-o-joe, sometimes even bad coffee tastes great.<br>
<br>
Gasp, one other thing to add to that list of things with caffeine;<br>
<br>
Dexatrim diet pill, 400mg (much more effective than no-doze).<br>
